The Core Idea
A frequency map is just the answer to one question:

"how many times does each character appear?"

s = "aabbc"

frequency map = {
    'a' ‚Üí 2,
    'b' ‚Üí 2,
    'c' ‚Üí 1
}
That is it. You build that map, then you answer whatever the problem asks by reading from it.

Building the Map ‚Äî The One Pattern You Reuse Everywhere
javaMap<Character, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
    freq.put(c, freq.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);
}
The key line is freq.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1. It means:

"get the current count for this character. if it does not exist yet, start from 0. then add 1."

This is the only building block. Every problem below just uses this map differently.

Problem 1 ‚Äî Duplicate Characters
Question: find all characters that appear more than once.
s = "programming"
duplicates = [r, g, m]
javapublic List<Character> findDuplicates(String s) {
    Map<Character, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();

    // build the map
    for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
        freq.put(c, freq.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);
    }

    // read from the map ‚Äî anything with count > 1 is a duplicate
    List<Character> duplicates = new ArrayList<>();
    for (Map.Entry<Character, Integer> entry : freq.entrySet()) {
        if (entry.getValue() > 1) {
            duplicates.add(entry.getKey());
        }
    }

    return duplicates;
}
