The int[26] Alternative ‚Äî Faster for Lowercase Letters
When the problem guarantees only lowercase letters (a-z), skip the HashMap entirely. Use a fixed array of size 26.
javaint[] freq = new int[26];

// 'a' maps to index 0
// 'b' maps to index 1
// 'z' maps to index 25
// the trick: subtract 'a' to get the index

for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
    freq[c - 'a']++;
}
The anagram check becomes:
javapublic boolean isAnagram(String s, String t) {
    if (s.length() != t.length()) return false;

    int[] freq = new int[26];

    for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
        freq[s.charAt(i) - 'a']++;  // increment for s
        freq[t.charAt(i) - 'a']--;  // decrement for t
    }

    for (int count : freq) {
        if (count != 0) return false;
    }

    return true;
}
c - 'a' works because characters are just numbers in Java:
'a' = 97
'b' = 98
'c' = 99

'a' - 'a' = 0   ‚Üí index 0
'b' - 'a' = 1   ‚Üí index 1
'c' - 'a' = 2   ‚Üí index 2

When to Use Which
Input has only lowercase letters    ‚Üí int[26] array ‚Äî faster, cleaner
Input has any characters            ‚Üí HashMap
Order of first appearance matters   ‚Üí LinkedHashMap
You need to check two strings       ‚Üí build from one, tear down with other
You need to find something specific ‚Üí build the map, then loop and check

The One Mental Model That Ties It All Together
Every HashMap frequency problem is two steps:
STEP 1 ‚Äî BUILD
  loop through the string
  count every character into the map

STEP 2 ‚Äî READ
  loop through the map
  answer the question using the counts
The build step never changes. Only what you do in the read step changes per problem. Once you see that, every new problem is just "what am I reading for?"Sonnet 4.6